by Maria Soccoro Ingco¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

The goal of the investigation was to determine the flight performance of carriers, such as the overall on-time arrival rate, typical causes of delays and the busiest months in the year.

The dataset used for this analysis was taken from Bureau of Transportation Statistics.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The original dataset contained a total of 22 columns and 18113 rows. After removing unnamed/empty rows and columns, the final dataset used for analysis contained 21 columns and 18105 rows.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The arrival and delay information.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The dataset had year and month information. Also, the arrivals and delays data were both present in total count and total time.

# Create a chart showing counts of each carrier
tick_props = np.arange(0, max_prop, 0.02)
tick_names = ['{:0.2f}'.format(v) for v in tick_props]
base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]

plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))
sb.countplot(data=t_flight, y='carrier', order=sort_carrier, color=base_color)

for i in range (carrier_count.shape[0]):
    count = carrier_count[i]
    pct_string = '{:0.1f}%'.format(100*count/n_carrier)
    plt.text(count+1, i, pct_string, va='center')

plt.xlabel('Count', size=12)
plt.xlim(0, 2000)
plt.ylabel('Carrier', size=12)
plt.title('Carrier Distribution from 2015-2019', size=16);

Delta Air (DL), American Airlines (AA) and United Airlines (UA) were the top 3 carriers from the list. These carriers were also considered as the top carriers in the world in terms of fleet size and seat capacity.

By transforming the arrivals data, it was observed that it also had a normal distribution.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The carrier and airport distributions were normal. However, it was not the same for arrivals and delays distribution, both of which were highly skewed to the right.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

Because of the unsual distributions for arrivals and delays, transformation was necessary to have a better view on the distribution. However, it can only be done on the arrivals data. There were instances that no delays happened so certain cells in delays had '0' entries. Thus transformation was not possible.

Bivariate Exploration¶

  • Determine the total and average arrivals and delays per year
In [14]:
# Create chart showing total arrivals per year
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
plot1 = t_flight.groupby(['year'])['arr_flights'].sum().plot.barh()

for p in plot1.patches:
    width = p.get_width()
    plt.text(1.09*p.get_width(), p.get_y()+0.5*p.get_height(),
             '{:1.2f}'.format(width),
             ha='center', va='center')
    
plt.title('Total Arrivals', size = 18, pad = 20)
plt.ylabel('')
sb.despine();

There had been a significant increase in the number of arrivals between 2017 and 2018. The trend continued to increase in 2019 but on a much lower rate.

  • Identify the overall all on-time performance.
In [18]:
# Get sum of total arrivals and delays
arrival = t_flight.arr_flights.sum()
delay = t_flight[['carrier_ct', ' weather_ct', 'nas_ct', 'security_ct', 'late_aircraft_ct', 
                  'arr_cancelled', 'arr_diverted']].sum().sum()
In [19]:
# Compute on-time arrival rate and delayed arrival rate
del_rate = delay / arrival
arr_rate = 1 - del_rate
In [20]:
# Create a chart showing on-time performance
plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
plt.pie([arr_rate, del_rate], labels=['On-time', 'Delayed'], autopct='%1.1f%%', startangle=90, counterclock=False)
plt.title('On-time Arrival Performance from 2015-2019', size = 16);

Flights arrived on-time ~80% of the time.

In [21]:
# Compute percentage of each cause of delay
carrier = 100 * t_flight.carrier_ct.sum() / delay
weather = 100 * t_flight[[' weather_ct']].sum() / delay
nas = 100 * t_flight.nas_ct.sum() / delay
security = 100 * t_flight.security_ct.sum() / delay
late = 100 * t_flight.late_aircraft_ct.sum() / delay
cancelled = 100 * t_flight.arr_cancelled.sum() / delay
diverted = 100 * t_flight.arr_diverted.sum() / delay

# Create a list containing rate of each reason for delay
list = [['Carrier', carrier], ['Weather', weather], ['NAS', nas], ['Security', security], ['Late Aircraft', late], 
        ['Cancelled', cancelled], ['Diverted', diverted]]

reason = pd.DataFrame(list, columns=['reason', 'rate'], dtype=float)

# Sort data in descending order
del_order = reason.sort_values(by = ['rate'], ascending = False, inplace = True)

# Create a chart showing the different reasons for delay
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plot2 = sb.barplot(x='reason', y='rate', data=reason, palette='Blues_r')

for p in plot2.patches:
    plot2.annotate(format(p.get_height(), '.1f'), 
                   (p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2., p.get_height()), 
                   ha = 'center', va = 'center', 
                   xytext = (0, 9), textcoords = 'offset points')

plt.title('Reasons for Delay', size = 18, pad = 10)
plt.xlabel('')
plt.xticks(size=12)
plt.ylabel('Rate', size = 14)
plt.yticks([], [])
sb.despine();

The reasons for delay in descending order: national aviation system (NAS), late aircraft, carrier delay, cancelled flight, weather delay, diverted flights and security delay.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

The total number of arrivals and delays showed a significant increase in 2018. However, the average arrivals per year had a very little change. The increasing trend in average delays, on the other hand, was much more visible than that of the average arrivals.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

Flights arrived on-time ~80% of the time and the top reason for delay was due to national aviation system at 32.9%, which according to Bureau of Transportation Statistics includes weather condition, high volume of flights, and closed runways.

for p in plot3.patches:
    plot3.annotate(format(p.get_height(), '.1f'), 
                   (p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2., p.get_height()), 
                   ha = 'center', va = 'center', 
                   xytext = (0, 9), textcoords = 'offset points')

plt.title('Average Time of Delay', size = 18, pad = 15)
plt.xlabel('')
plt.ylabel('Minutes', size = 14)
plt.xticks(size=12)
plt.yticks([], [])
sb.despine();

On average, late aircraft was causing the longest time delay, ~5,000 minutes. Cancelled and diverted flights have no time attribute, thus were removed from the list.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

In general, the higher number of arrivals, the higher number and the longer time of delays. It was seen that during the months of June to August that the highest number of arrivals and delays and the longest time delays were recorded.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

Interestingly, while Delta Air had the most number of arrivals, it was ExpressJet Airlines that had the most delays. Another observation was while it was national aviation system that had caused the most number of delays, it was delayed aircraft that had the longest delays, averaging approximately a 5,000 minutes or equivalent to 3.5 days.
